With AVX512, each packed element is 64 bytes (16 × 4-byte BabyBear). Reading 4 packed elements simultaneously means reading 64 bytes from each of 4 regions = 256 bytes per loop iteration. The 4 regions are:
- group0: 256 KiB region starting at submat[0]
- group1: 256 KiB region starting at submat[256 KiB]
- group2: 256 KiB region starting at submat[512 KiB]
- group3: 256 KiB region starting at submat[768 KiB]

The hardware prefetcher needs to track 4 independent streams (each 256 KiB). This is well within the 8-12 stream limit on modern CPUs (e.g., Intel's Superfly prefetcher).

Memory bandwidth: 4 × 256 KiB = 1 MiB read + 1 MiB write per thread vs current 1 MiB + 1 MiB (layer_rev=9) + 1 MiB + 1 MiB (layer_rev=8) = 4 MiB per thread. So fusion saves 2/4 = 50% bandwidth for these two layers.

